From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Michael Verrilli <msv@pobox.com>
Date: Tue, 21 Apr 2026 21:02:21 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ml/backend/ggml: port the TurboQuant CUDA kernels to Metal
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Adds Metal Shading Language implementations of every TurboQuant GGML op
so Apple Silicon matches the CUDA feature set. New kernels in
ml/backend/ggml/ggml/src/ggml-metal/ggml-metal.metal:

  * kernel_tq_encode / kernel_tq_encode_v / kernel_tq_encode_outlier
  * kernel_tq_dequant / kernel_tq_dequant_outlier
  * kernel_tq_fattn_vec_f16   (f16 V, packed K)
  * kernel_tq_fattn_vec_packed (packed K and V)

Pipeline accessors go through ggml-metal-device.{h,cpp}, dispatch
through ggml-metal-ops.cpp. supports_op returns true for all TQ ops when
simdgroup reduction is available (every Apple GPU that ships with the
unified Metal shader-compiler backend).

Extend tq_device_scan to accept Metal: Apple GPUs are natively 32-wide
SIMD, so the same __shfl_sync width=32 the CUDA kernels assume maps
1-to-1 to simd_shuffle / simd_shuffle_xor on Metal.

Also adds a preferFusedAttention flag on ggmlTQCompressedK, set when
the scanner reports Metal. The DequantKV + stock FA path writes a full
cache-sized f16 intermediate tensor that stock FA then reads back — on
Metal's unified memory this doubles KV bandwidth at long context.
TurboQuantCache.Get() uses the flag to prefer the K+V fused inline-
decode path on Metal (path 2) instead of DequantKV (path 1). CUDA
behaviour is unchanged.
